<body>
    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>Best Baits for Rainbow Trout</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">A comprehensive guide to selecting the right bait for successful rainbow trout fishing in any season and condition</p>
        </header>
        
        <div class="content">
            <div class="main-content">
                <h2>Top Rainbow Trout Baits</h2>
                
                <div class="bait-card">
                    <h3>PowerBait Dough</h3>
                    <div class="bait-image">üß¥</div>
                    <p><span class="rating">Effectiveness: 9/10</span></p>
                    <p>Specially formulated dough bait that rainbow trout find irresistible. Available in various colors and scents. Best used with a small treble hook suspended off the bottom.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Stocked trout, still fishing</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="bait-card">
                    <h3>Live Worms</h3>
                    <div class="bait-image">ü™±</div>
                    <p><span class="rating">Effectiveness: 10/10</span></p>
                    <p>Nightcrawlers, red worms, and garden worms are natural trout favorites. Use a single hook and enough weight to keep the worm near the bottom where trout feed.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> All trout, river fishing</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="bait-card">
                    <h3>Salmon Eggs</h3>
                    <div class="bait-image">üç£</div>
                    <p><span class="rating">Effectiveness: 8/10</span></p>
                    <p>Natural bait that mimics the eggs trout would naturally feed on. Particularly effective during spawning seasons. Use a small hook and fish near the bottom.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> River fishing, spawning season</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="bait-card">
                    <h3>Minnows and Small Fish</h3>
                    <div class="bait-image">üêü</div>
                    <p><span class="rating">Effectiveness: 9/10</span></p>
                    <p>Larger rainbow trout are predatory and will strike at small fish. Use live or dead minnows with a quick-strike rig for best results.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Larger trout, lake fishing</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="bait-card">
                    <h3>Insects (Grasshoppers, Crickets)</h3>
                    <div class="bait-image">ü¶ó</div>
                    <p><span class="rating">Effectiveness: 7/10</span></p>
                    <p>During summer months, terrestrial insects make excellent trout bait. Use a float to keep them near the surface where trout are looking for them.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Summer fishing, surface feeding</p>
                </div>
                
                <h2>Seasonal Bait Recommendations</h2>
                <table class="season-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Season</th>
                            <th>Recommended Baits</th>
                            <th>Fishing Tips</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Spring</td>
                            <td>PowerBait, Worms, Salmon Eggs</td>
                            <td>Fish shallower areas as water warms; trout are more active</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Summer</td>
                            <td>Insects, Minnows, Nightcrawlers</td>
                            <td>Early morning and evening are best; fish deeper during hot days</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Fall</td>
                            <td>Minnows, Worms, Salmon Eggs</td>
                            <td>Trout feed aggressively before winter; excellent fishing time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Winter</td>
                            <td>PowerBait, Salmon Eggs, Small Worms</td>
                            <td>Fish slowly and near the bottom; trout are less active</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                
                <div class="pro-tip">
                    <h3>Pro Tip: Match the Hatch</h3>
                    <p>Observe what natural food sources are available in the water you're fishing. If you see insects hatching or small fish swimming, try to match your bait to what the trout are naturally feeding on.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="sidebar">
                <h2>Quick Tips</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use light line (4-6 lb test) for better presentation</li>
                    <li>Keep your bait fresh and natural-looking</li>
                    <li>Adjust bait size to match trout size</li>
                    <li>Change locations if you're not getting bites</li>
                    <li>Be patient - trout can be selective feeders</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h2>Best Times to Fish</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Early morning (dawn until 2 hours after)</li>
                    <li>Late afternoon (2 hours before dusk until dark)</li>
                    <li>Overcast days (trout are less wary)</li>
                    <li>During light rain (insects get washed into water)</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h2>Essential Gear</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Light or ultralight spinning rod</li>
                    <li>Small hooks (size 8-14)</li>
                    <li>Split shot weights</li>
                    <li>Floats/bobbers for suspended bait</li>
                    <li>Landing net</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
        
